After high school, I went to the
University of Pittsburgh.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:29.940
Where is it? Down there?

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:30.780
There,

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:33.930
where I ate at the "Dirty O," the
Original

00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:35.960
Hot Dog. Anybody, Original Hot Dog
fans?

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:38.220
You like the French fries better,

00:17:38.176 --> 00:17:39.220
or you like the hot dogs better?

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:42.640
French fries? Raise your hand.

00:17:44.355 --> 00:17:44.405
Hot dogs?

00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:48.040
Alright. French fries win the day.

00:17:50.145 --> 00:17:51.429
Ate at the "Dirty O," had a
girlfriend

00:17:51.850 --> 00:17:53.380
or two, and worked at the Fine Arts
Library

00:17:54.040 --> 00:17:55.820
and got an honors degree in
economics.

00:17:57.220 --> 00:17:59.080
After Pitt, I worked at a bank for a
little

00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:00.879
and then came to Carnegie Mellon for
my

00:18:01.030 --> 00:18:01.530
MBA.

00:18:02.770 --> 00:18:03.910
Even though it was hard work,

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:05.680
I actually loved this place.

00:18:06.910 --> 00:18:08.409
It was also the foundation for
everything

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:10.360
I've done professionally since then.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:12.490
This place.

00:18:12.610 --> 00:18:14.379
This place gave me the

00:18:14.500 --> 00:18:16.120
tools I needed to be successful.

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:17.150
It really did.

00:18:17.320 --> 00:18:17.830
I'm not kidding.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:20.940
Well,

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:22.940
when I graduated I kind of liked
markets

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:23.030
and investments,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:24.809
so I tried to get a job

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:26.070
with Goldman Sachs,

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:27.630
but they rejected me.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:29.300
Didn't get a job there.

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:32.350
We'll come back to Goldman Sachs a
little later.

00:18:33.990 --> 00:18:36.030
So after I got my MBA,

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:38.030
I made an unusual choice at the
time.

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:40.700
I went to work for Republic Steel.

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:43.470
That wasn't a great time for steel,

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:45.060
but I knew I would be exposed to a
lot,

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:46.190
and I really wanted to learn.

00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:49.559
About three months after

00:18:49.830 --> 00:18:51.140
I got to Republic Steel,

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:53.780
they gave a 7 percent
across-the-board

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:55.680
pay cut.

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:57.930
Pay cut.

00:18:58.800 --> 00:18:59.900
All my business school buddies,

00:18:59.856 --> 00:19:01.800
all my business school friends,

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:03.270
called me up and said,

00:19:03.510 --> 00:19:03.950
"Great choice,

00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:04.870
Tep!"

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:08.739
In two years, Republic Steel had to
merge

00:19:09.010 --> 00:19:10.050
to avoid bankruptcy,

00:19:10.750 --> 00:19:12.020
but it was a great choice.

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:14.649
And in those two years that they
were trying to save

00:19:14.860 --> 00:19:16.629
the company, Republic did

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:18.309
more finance deals than it had in
its previous

00:19:18.820 --> 00:19:19.930
100-year history.

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:21.820
And I learned from each one of them.

00:19:22.970 --> 00:19:23.830
There's a lesson here.

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:25.340
In life,

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:26.210
in life,

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:28.460
get all the experience you can.

00:19:29.270 --> 00:19:30.859
While you're young, go for the
experience versus

00:19:31.220 --> 00:19:31.760
a paycheck.

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:35.359
That kind of experience got me a job
at a

00:19:35.420 --> 00:19:37.780
mutual fund specializing in
distressed companies,

00:19:38.210 --> 00:19:40.430
and eventually in the door

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:42.170
of Goldman Sachs,

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:45.400
where in a short time,

00:19:45.790 --> 00:19:46.989
because of my previous job
experience

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:48.090
and cutting-edge things, cutting
edge things

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:50.620
I learned at CMU,

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:52.240
I advanced quickly

00:19:52.270 --> 00:19:54.310
and became the head trader at
Goldman's junk desk.

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:57.430
That gave me more status than I knew
at that time,

00:19:57.820 --> 00:19:59.800
but what I really wanted was to
become a partner.

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:03.390
I was up for partner for a few times

00:20:03.600 --> 00:20:04.290
but never made it.

00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:07.529
One of the reasons was I had to

00:20:07.590 --> 00:20:09.320
refuse a powerful partner's request.

00:20:09.276 --> 00:20:09.325
The story is this:

00:20:12.680 --> 00:20:14.090
The partner had started a new fund

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:16.590
to invest in bankrupt companies,

00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:18.090
and I was supposed to make the
trades for him.

00:20:18.990 --> 00:20:20.699
He was also the partner who
controlled our restricted

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:21.540
lists.

00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:23.789
That's the list of companies where
you might have some

00:20:23.970 --> 00:20:24.660
conflicts

00:20:24.900 --> 00:20:26.320
or some sensitive information.

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:29.129
He asked me to buy a company that he
had

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:31.340
just removed from the restricted
list

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:32.780
that day, that day.

00:20:33.940 --> 00:20:34.800
It didn't seem right.

00:20:35.890 --> 00:20:36.430
In fact,

00:20:36.850 --> 00:20:37.509
I went to our legal department

00:20:37.960 --> 00:20:39.700
and told them what was going on.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:42.560
They said it would be okay after a
lot of

00:20:42.710 --> 00:20:43.490
back and forth,

00:20:44.150 --> 00:20:45.950
but it still didn't feel right to
me.

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:48.100
So, I refused again.

00:20:49.990 --> 00:20:50.940
I didn't get fired,

00:20:51.940 --> 00:20:53.230
but when I came up for partner,

00:20:53.290 --> 00:20:54.190
I got shot down.

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:57.090
And I was incredibly upset.

00:20:58.200 --> 00:20:58.950
But you know what,

00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:00.360
you know what?

00:21:01.290 --> 00:21:02.230
It turned out alright.

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:06.530
Because I didn't end up a partner

00:21:07.010 --> 00:21:07.790
at Goldman Sachs,

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:09.880
I started my own company 25

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:11.420
years ago, in 1993,

00:21:11.450 --> 00:21:12.310
called Appaloosa

00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:15.109
and ended up doing something that
was a lot more

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:15.740
fun

00:21:16.460 --> 00:21:18.890
and made my life better in so

00:21:18.980 --> 00:21:20.330
many ways.

00:21:22.060 --> 00:21:22.670
In life,

00:21:23.110 --> 00:21:23.750
in life,

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:25.050
do what's right.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:27.120
Really, do what's right,

00:21:27.610 --> 00:21:28.470
and it won't hurt you.

00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:30.990
Just keep your priorities straight.

00:21:32.570 --> 00:21:34.250
You know I keep saying in life,

00:21:35.090 --> 00:21:36.049
but really, as I said before,

00:21:36.410 --> 00:21:37.055
there are many lives.

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:40.720
I've had an incredible life from
humble beginnings.

00:21:41.500 --> 00:21:43.000
I've raised three great kids,

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:44.590
have a woman I love.

00:21:45.640 --> 00:21:46.989
I've had a successful business
career

00:21:46.990 --> 00:21:48.579
and incredible philanthropic

00:21:49.420 --> 00:21:50.110
endeavors.

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:52.030
And now I am speaking to you

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:53.890
as a newly named doctorate,

00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:55.719
and I am on the verge of being named
an NFL

00:21:56.110 --> 00:21:56.390
owner.

